NutriJIA Feasibility, Safety, and Exploratory Clinical Analysis of a Nutritional Intervention

Introduction

Back to Table of Content

Nutritional interventions in pediatric and adolescent populations are increasingly explored as low-threshold strategies to support health and disease management. Before drawing conclusions about clinical effectiveness, it is essential to establish whether an intervention is feasible, well-adhered to, and safeespecially when biological safety markers and anthropometric parameters may change over time.

NutriJIA evaluates a structured nutritional intervention compared to a control condition with repeated assessments at predefined time points, most prominently:

  • baseline visit: visite_0_wo0
  • post-intervention follow-up: visite_1_wo12

In this notebook, feasibility is operationalised primarily through adherence metrics. Safety is evaluated using anthropometric and laboratory markers, including:

  • weight / BMI
  • Vitamin B12
  • transferrin saturation
  • zinc
  • beta-carotene

The analyses focus on within-person change from baseline to post-intervention and on between-group differences (intervention vs. control), typically with baseline adjustment.

Objective

Back to Table of Content

The primary goal of this analysis is not to maximize predictive performance, but to provide a transparent, reproducible evaluation of feasibility and safety and to generate exploratory clinical signals that can inform future confirmatory studies.

More specifically, we aim to:

  1. Construct an analysis-ready participant-level dataset with:

    • group assignment (intervention vs. control)
    • adherence metrics (definition depends on available data)
    • safety endpoints (weight/BMI, Vitamin B12, transferrin saturation, zinc, beta-carotene)
    • key baseline covariates for adjustment (as pre-specified)

  2. Perform the main feasibility and safety analyses:

    • Quantify adherence and summarise feasibility descriptively (primary).
    • Compare safety markers from baseline to post-intervention between groups using baseline-adjusted models (primary).

  3. Perform exploratory clinical analyses (secondary):

    • Explore additional outcomes (if available) using the same baseline-adjusted framework.
    • Treat all non-safety endpoints as hypothesis-generating.

  4. Integrate results into a coherent interpretation:

    • Emphasise feasibility/safety conclusions and uncertainty.
    • Clearly separate primary (feasibility/safety) from exploratory findings.

Methodological Role

Back to Table of Content

This notebook is the central, reproducible record of:

  • how raw study exports are cleaned and reshaped,
  • how adherence, safety endpoints, and covariates are defined, and
  • how baseline-adjusted group comparisons are implemented and reported.

Structurally, we distinguish:

  1. Data processing

    • Import and harmonise visit-level data
    • Derive an analysis-ready dataset (e.g., one row per participant per visit and/or one row per participant with change scores)

  2. Exploratory data analysis

    • Missingness and distributions
    • Study characteristics and baseline comparability (Table 1-style summary)

  3. Primary analyses: feasibility & safety

    • Adherence summaries (feasibility)
    • Baseline-adjusted between-group comparisons for safety endpoints

  4. Secondary analyses: exploratory clinical outcomes

    • Additional baseline-adjusted models (clearly labeled exploratory)
    • Sensitivity analyses (e.g., alternative adherence definitions, missing-data scenarios)

  5. Interpretation

    • Summary of feasibility and safety evidence
    • Transparent reporting of limitations and implications for future trials

Derive a clean group variable from grp

In[9]:
# Functin to extract group assignment from the grp column
# The grp column encodes group assignment using a pattern like
# nJIA-P-0-01  for control
# nJIA-P-1-02  for intervention
#
# There may be minor typos such as missing dashes
# We will extract the first standalone 0 or 1 after the nJIA-P marker
# If extraction fails, group will be missing and we will flag those rows

def extract_group_from_grp(value):
    """
    Extract group indicator from the grp string.

    Expected patterns include
    nJIA-P-0-01
    nJIA-P-1-02

    Also tolerates minor formatting issues such as missing a dash
    nJIA-P1-15

    Returns
    0 for control
    1 for intervention
    np.nan if parsing fails
    """
    if pd.isna(value):
        return np.nan

    s = str(value).strip()

    # First attempt
    # Look for nJIA then P then any separators then capture 0 or 1
    m = re.search(r"nJIA\s*[-_]*\s*P\s*[-_]*\s*([01])", s, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    if m:
        return int(m.group(1))

    # Second attempt
    # A more permissive fallback that captures any 0 or 1 that is surrounded by separators
    m2 = re.search(r"(?:^|[-_])([01])(?:[-_]|$)", s)
    if m2:
        return int(m2.group(1))

    return np.nan

# Tokens interpreted as missing values across the dataset (case-insensitive handling is done below)
MISSING_TOKENS = {
    "x", "X",
    "", " ",
    "na", "n/a", "NA", "N/A",
    "nan", "NaN",
    ".", "-",
    "None", "NULL", "null",
}
In[18]:
# Tokens specific to adherence columns indicating "not applicable by design"
ADHERENCE_NOT_APPLICABLE_TOKENS = {
    "Kontrolle", "kontrolle",
    "Intervention", "intervention",
}
In[19]:
# Function to clean string entries in a pandas Series
def clean_string_tokens(series: pd.Series) -> pd.Series:
    """
    Standardize text-like entries and mark missing tokens as NaN.

    - strips whitespace
    - converts decimal commas to decimal points
    - converts a set of known tokens (x, NA, ., - ...) to np.nan
    - keeps other strings as-is (numeric conversion happens elsewhere)
    """
    # Keep original missing as missing
    s = series.copy()

    # Work in a string view but avoid turning true NaN into "nan" permanently
    s_str = s.astype("string").str.strip()

    # Harmonize decimal commas (German exports)
    s_str = s_str.str.replace(",", ".", regex=False)

    # Replace common missing tokens (robust to case and whitespace)
    # We compare after lowercasing
    missing_lower = {str(t).strip().lower() for t in MISSING_TOKENS}

    # Create a lowered view for comparison
    s_lower = s_str.str.lower()

    # Set missing where token matches
    s_clean = s_str.mask(s_lower.isin(missing_lower), other=pd.NA)

    # Return as object with np.nan for compatibility with numeric coercion and pandas ops
    return s_clean.astype("object").where(s_clean.notna(), np.nan)
In[20]:
# Function to clean and coerce a Series to numeric
def clean_to_numeric(series: pd.Series) -> pd.Series:
    """
    Clean a Series and coerce it to numeric.
    Non-parseable entries become missing (np.nan).
    """
    s = clean_string_tokens(series)
    return pd.to_numeric(s, errors="coerce")
In[21]:
# Function to clean adherence columns and coerce to numeric
def clean_adherence_to_numeric(series: pd.Series) -> pd.Series:
    """
    Clean adherence columns and coerce to numeric.

    Special handling:
    - "Kontrolle"/"Intervention" are placeholders (not adherence values) -> missing
    - remaining values coerced to numeric
    """
    s = clean_string_tokens(series)

    # Replace not-applicable placeholders (case-insensitive)
    na_tokens_lower = {t.lower() for t in ADHERENCE_NOT_APPLICABLE_TOKENS}
    s_lower = pd.Series(s, index=series.index).astype("string").str.lower()
    s = pd.Series(s, index=series.index).astype("object").mask(s_lower.isin(na_tokens_lower), other=np.nan)

    return pd.to_numeric(s, errors="coerce")

# Spaghetti plot function
def spaghetti_plot(
    df,
    outcome,
    ylabel,
    title
):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Individual trajectories
    for pid, d in df.groupby("study_id"):
        plt.plot(
            d["time"],
            d[outcome],
            color="grey",
            alpha=0.4,
            linewidth=1
        )

    # Group means
    for group, d in df.groupby("group"):
        mean_traj = (
            d
            .groupby("time")[outcome]
            .mean()
        )
        plt.plot(
            mean_traj.index,
            mean_traj.values,
            linewidth=3,
            label=group
        )

    plt.xlabel("Time")
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(title="Group")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Boxplot with dot overlay function
def delta_box_dot(df, delta_col, title, ylabel):
    groups = ["control", "intervention"]
    data = [df.loc[df["group"] == g, delta_col].dropna() for g in groups]

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.boxplot(data, labels=groups, showfliers=False)

    # dot overlay with deterministic jitter (so reruns look identical)
    for i, g in enumerate(groups, start=1):
        y = df.loc[df["group"] == g, delta_col].dropna().values
        n = len(y)
        if n == 0:
            continue
        jitter = np.linspace(-0.08, 0.08, n)  # deterministic jitter
        plt.scatter(np.full(n, i) + jitter, y)

    plt.axhline(0, linewidth=1)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Scatter plot baseline vs delta function
def baseline_vs_delta(df, baseline_col, delta_col, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    for g in df["group"].dropna().unique():
        d = df[df["group"] == g].dropna(subset=[baseline_col, delta_col])
        plt.scatter(d[baseline_col], d[delta_col], label=g)

    plt.axhline(0, linewidth=1)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(title="Group")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Integrated interpretation: In this exploratory pilot analysis, baseline-adjusted linear models did not provide evidence for a beneficial effect of the intervention on global patient- or physician-rated disease activity at study endpoint. Observed outcome variability was largely explained by baseline disease activity and marked inter-individual heterogeneity, with wide confidence intervals around group estimates.

# Safety delta plot function
def safety_delta_plot(df, var, ylabel):
    delta_col = f"{var}_delta"

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    groups = ["control", "intervention"]
    data = [
        df.loc[df["group"] == g, delta_col].dropna()
        for g in groups
    ]

    plt.boxplot(data, labels=groups, showfliers=False)

    for i, g in enumerate(groups, start=1):
        y = df.loc[df["group"] == g, delta_col].dropna().values
        n = len(y)
        if n > 0:
            jitter = np.linspace(-0.08, 0.08, n)
            plt.scatter(np.full(n, i) + jitter, y)

    plt.axhline(0)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(f"Change in {var} (V2  V0)")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Spaghetti plot for safety variables
def spaghetti_safety(df, var, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    for pid, d in df.groupby("study_id"):
        plt.plot(d["time"], d[var], color="grey", alpha=0.4)

    for g, d in df.groupby("group"):
        mean_traj = d.groupby("time")[var].mean()
        plt.plot(mean_traj.index, mean_traj.values, linewidth=3, label=g)

    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(f"{var} over time")
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def adherence_scatter(df, outcome, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 4))
    plt.scatter(df[adherence_col], df[outcome])
    plt.axhline(0)
    plt.xlabel("Adherence score (TV1)")

    plt.title(f"Adherence vs change in {outcome}")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Self-reported adherence was assessed descriptively within each study arm during the respective intervention phases. In the intervention group, adherence scores ranged from 1 to 5 (median 2.75), indicating moderate adherence with substantial inter-individual variability. In the waitlist control group, adherence during the delayed intervention phase ranged from 0 to 5 (median 3.0), with a similar spread. Due to structural differences in timing and applicability of adherence assessments across groups, adherence measures were not directly compared and were not included in outcome models.
